\contentsline {deleted}{Deleted~(pinn): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\begin {equation} r = \frac {\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ (x_i - \bar {x})(y_i - \bar {y})}{\sqrt {\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ (x_i - \bar {x})^2}\sqrt {\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ (y_i - \bar {y})^2}}, \end {equation}}}{8}{section*.3}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(pinn): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{\begin {equation} r = \frac {\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _i (x_i - \bar {x})(y_i - \bar {y})}{\bigl [\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _i (x_i - \bar {x})^2\bigr ]^{1/2}\,\bigl [\DOTSB \sum@ \slimits@ _i (y_i - \bar {y})^2\bigr ]^{1/2}}, \end {equation}}}{8}{section*.4}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(pinn): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{; the denominator is the product of the two independent sample standard deviations}}{8}{section*.5}%
\contentsline {replaced}{Replaced~(pinn): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{FourierPINN surrogate for WSS prediction. \textbf {Top branch:} the input coordinates $(x,y,z)$ enter a random Fourier feature map $\gamma (\mathbf {x})$ (m=64 frequencies, $\sigma =10$, output dimension 131), are processed by a trunk of 6 residual blocks (two SiLU-activated linear layers per block with 48 hidden units and a skip connection; see Fig.~\ref {fig:pinn_resblock} for detail), and emerge as five output heads $u,v,w,p,\tau _w$. \textbf {Bottom branch:} the total loss $\mathcal {L}=\lambda _{\text {wss}}\mathcal {L}_{\text {wss}}+\lambda _{\text {vel}}\mathcal {L}_{\text {vel}}+\lambda _{\text {NS}}\mathcal {L}_{\text {NS}}+\lambda _{\text {cont}}\mathcal {L}_{\text {cont}}+\lambda _\tau \mathcal {L}_\tau $ aggregates the five components. The data losses ($\mathcal {L}_{\text {wss}}$, $\mathcal {L}_{\text {vel}}$) tap directly from the output heads at supervised CFD points (wall surface for $\tau _w$, mesh interior for $u,v,w$). The physics losses ($\mathcal {L}_{\text {NS}}$, $\mathcal {L}_{\text {cont}}$, $\mathcal {L}_\tau $) are evaluated at a separate set of collocation points sampled from the fluid domain; the dashed arrow labelled \emph {autodiff} marks where second-order spatial derivatives of $u,v,w,p$ are obtained by automatic differentiation through the trunk.}}{11}{section*.7}%
\contentsline {added}{Added~(pinn): \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{The PINN surrogate constructed in this study targets the Newtonian CFD ground truth and uses the constant-viscosity momentum residual (Eq.~\ref {eq:ns_residual_x}) and WSS-from-gradient consistency (Eq.~\ref {eq:wss_phys}) introduced above; the same dynamic viscosity $\mu = 0.0035$~Pa$\cdot $s is used in the data-driven CFD targets and in the physics-loss residual, so the surrogate is trained against governing equations consistent with its training data. A non-Newtonian Carreau--Yasuda variant of these losses, in which $\mu _{\mathrm {eff}}(\dot \gamma )$ is evaluated pointwise from the local strain-rate tensor of the predicted velocity field via the closure of Eq.~\ref {eq:carreau_yasuda}, is the physically correct formulation when training against Carreau--Yasuda CFD data. Because the present PINN training set contains only Newtonian CFD ground truth, we do not present a Carreau--Yasuda PINN surrogate here; the supporting code (helper \texttt {carreau\_yasuda\_viscosity} in \texttt {src/physics.py}) is in place and we identify the non-Newtonian surrogate as the immediate next step once Carreau--Yasuda CFD ground truth is available across all patients. The Newtonian-vs-Carreau--Yasuda comparison reported elsewhere in this manuscript (Tables \ref {tab:awawss}--\ref {tab:iqr_wss} and the corresponding contour figures) is therefore a CFD-side result.}}{13}{section*.9}%
